 </p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub54.ezboard.com/udoldrumstormhaze.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Doldrum Stormhaze</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Froglok Guk Knight</span><br>  Posts: 3<br> <font color=#00CCFF>(10/4/02 4:38:59 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub54.ezboard.com/fquelliousquaterstherebirthfrm13.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=559.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> The New Raid System</span><hr size=1> Personally, I am thrilled to see a system like this go into place. Let me outline a few of the reasons.<br>
<br>
This works to ameliorate several issues, above and beyond the issue of shared experience gain.<br>
<br>
The first reason is that a raid leader can control looting and keep a tighter set of reins on the raid. The simple visual tool of being able to see raid groups and their formations is helpful, especially on larger raids.<br>
<br>
The second issue this ameliorates is what I consider the 'problem' of the KS group. I cannot count the times that people have over-spent mana, or pulled aggro causing ping-pong attempting to be 'the KS group'.<br>
<br>
The whole concept of a KS group causes a systemic concern because, though it does foster competition and potentially faster kills, it also fosters poor raid behavior. The consequences of this become most apparent when someone gets summoned and killed within the first few seconds of the fight other than the person slowing, tashing, or otherwise performing invaluable debuffing tasks which generate near instant aggro.<br>
<br>
Case in point: the overuse of rain spells, discs, etc. I cannot count the number of times casters in raids I have attended get summoned and killed due to over-using their rain spells in an attempt to slide more damage into the raid situation...or the number of times that a truly bad mob has shown up in camp either by accident (mispull, lag, what have you) and the raid has spent out most of it's mana and/or discs due to attempting to get a KS on the previous, easier mob that had been in camp.<br>
<br>
Though this behavior does not always result in a wipe-out, for the most part this becomes highly dangerous in situations where there is very little or no margin for error.<br>
<br>
The raid system reduces a raid down to what it really is...a vital team effort to attain goals which are unreachable by the standard six person party. Yes, you run the risk of people taking extended afk breaks during raids...but really, if someone is that inattentive, why are you raiding with them in the first place? Raids, which are for the most part a function of the guild system, are on a deeper level a facet of friendship displayed by a group of people joining together to accomplish a singular goal. Attending a raid, unless it is specifically directed (aka: *your* epic raid), means that you come knowing you may walk away with nothing in hand other than a feeling of accomplishment at defeating some large creature.<br>
<br>
If this goal does not fit into your plans...then why attend a raid? It defies logic to attend a raid and 'try' to earn experience with the KS group rather than form a solid six person group and *know* you will be gaining the experience every kill.<br>
<br>
By wiping out this systemic concern, it then becomes easier to teach and indoctrinate the newer raiders in the ways of efficient and methodical raiding. This is not to say that they will instantly become better raiders...instincts and battle awareness are not things one can 'train' someone in, it is garnered through experience and on some level a natural talent. It will significantly shorten the training and learning time for many new raiders by removing the troublesome first phases that many (not all) raiders experience where they feel that gaining experience on a raid is the *most* important aspect.<br>
<br>
I look forward to the new raid system, and I hope that it will help discourage some of the poor raid habits that float around out there, especially in pick up raids...which is for many people their first experience truly raiding.<br>
<br>
--dolly--<br>
<br>
Doldrum<br>
60 Sorceror of Karana<br>
Officer, Knights of Trinity  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub54.ezboard.com/uesmalyn.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Esmalyn</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>The Bitch Queen</span><br>  Posts: 497<br> <font color=#00CCFF>(10/4/02 4:59:39 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub54.ezboard.com/fquelliousquaterstherebirthfrm13.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=559.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Raiding exp</span><hr size=1> Gaethan, don't take it the wrong way but it seems as if you like to shoot yourself in the foot.<br>
